An interface class is one with no member variables and all pure virtual functions. These are often named starting with a capital I.A virtual base class is a base class that is only included once, no matter how many times it is inherited by an object.When a derived class is assigned to a base class object, the base class only receives a copy of the base portion of the derived class. This is called object slicing.Dynamic casting can be used to convert a pointer to a base class object into a pointer to a derived class object. This is called downcasting. A failed conversion will return a null pointer.The easiest way to overload operator<< for inherited classes is to write an overloaded operator<< for the most-base class, and then call a virtual member function to do the printing.Quiz timeEach of the following programs has some kind of defect. Inspect each program (visually, not by compiling) and determine what is wrong with the program. The output of each program is supposed to be “Derived”.1a)#include <iostream>

